### 1.2 Branding Application Rules

The branding configuration is applied consistently across the entire report. The cover page uses a **separate template** from the body pages. Body pages (page 2 onwards) share a common header and footer.

---

#### 1.2.1 Cover Page Architecture

The cover page is a distinct, visually rich template. It does **not** use the running header. The Oceanomatics project report template (used for technical reports such as the Reef Keeper DP upgrade) is the reference design. The following zones are defined:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  [TOP BAR]                                          │
│  Left: Client / underwriter reference block         │
│  Right: Year or document type label                 │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                     │
│         [VESSEL NAME — large title band]            │
│         Background: primary_colour                  │
│         [REPORT TYPE / STATUS BAND below]           │
│         Background: secondary_colour or dark grey   │
│                                                     │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                     │
│              [VESSEL PHOTOGRAPH]                    │
│              Full width, centred                    │
│                                                     │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  [BOTTOM INFO BOX — two columns]                    │
│  Left: Occurrence (date + nature of casualty)       │
│  Right: Claim's Reference | File No. | Report No.   │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Left: [REPORT STATUS BADGE]                        │
│  e.g. ● PRELIMINARY  or  ● FINAL                   │
│                                                     │
│  Right: Report Date: DD/MM/YYYY                     │
│         Prepared by: [Surveyor Name], [Firm]        │
│                                                     │
│  [FIRM LOGO] — bottom left, at full configured      │
│  display width                                      │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Cover page element rules:**

| Element | Rule |
|---------|------|
| Vessel name band | `primary_colour` background, white bold text, large font (≥32pt equivalent). Full width. |
| Report type band | Sits directly below the vessel name band. `secondary_colour` or dark charcoal background, white text. Contains the report subtitle (e.g. "H&M DAMAGE SURVEY REPORT — FINAL"). |
| Report status badge | Coloured pill or tag: PRELIMINARY = amber background; PROGRESS = blue; INTERIM = grey-blue; FINAL = green; SUPPLEMENTARY = orange. Must be prominent — not buried in body text. |
| Vessel photograph | Full content width, proportionally scaled, centred. Sourced from Document Vault (`is_cover_photo = true`). If no photo is tagged, the image zone is replaced by a coloured placeholder band. |
| Bottom info box | Light grey or lavender background. Two-column layout. Left: Occurrence. Right: Claim's Reference / Technical File No. / Report Version No. |
| Firm logo | `firm_logo`, displayed at `firm_logo_width_px`. Positioned bottom left. If the logo has a dark background, use the reverse/white version if provided. |
| Client reference block (top left) | Underwriter name and claim reference (not the vessel owner's logo — this is an insurance report, not a delivery receipt). Plain text, small font. |
| No running header | The cover page does **not** include the header that appears on body pages. |

---

#### 1.2.2 Running Header (Pages 2 Onwards)

Every body page carries a consistent three-element header, as established in the H&M report best practice analysis. This is the standard format applied across all report types produced by the platform.

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ [LOGO]              [Vessel Name — Report Type — Claim Ref]  │
│ top left            right-aligned, italic, secondary_colour  │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ (full-width rule in primary_colour, 1–2pt)                   │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

- **Logo:** `firm_logo` at approximately 30–35% of cover page display size. Top left. The header row height must accommodate the logo unclipped.
- **Document title text:** Right-aligned. Format: `[Vessel Name] — [Report Type] — [Claim Reference]`. Small font (9–10pt equivalent), `secondary_colour`, italics.
- **Separator rule:** Full content width below the header row in `primary_colour`, 1–2pt.
- **Implementation note:** Render as a single paragraph with a right-aligned tab stop — not as a table. A table structure risks clipping the logo and introduces inconsistent widths relative to the body content.

---

#### 1.2.3 Footer (All Pages)

```
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
This report is supplied without prejudice. Confidential — [Firm Name] — Page N of Total
```

- Horizontal rule above, in `primary_colour` or light grey
- Centred text, 8–9pt, grey (#757575)
- Page number format: `Page N of Total`
- The footer carries a passive **"without prejudice"** notice on every page. This is in addition to — not a substitute for — the formal WP designations at the cost approval points and in the Waiver section. Its purpose is to ensure that no individual page of the report, if extracted in isolation, can be read as a statement made without reservation.
- Full recommended footer text: *"This report is supplied without prejudice to any or all parties involved and shall not be copied or passed on to third parties without the express permission of [Firm Name]. — Page N of Total"*

> **See Section 8.3 for the full Without Prejudice placement protocol.** The footer line is a passive every-page notice. The three mandatory active placements are on Page 2, at the cost summary, and in the Waiver section.

